contains case counts, rates, and confidence intervals of unintentional carbon monoxide poisoning (CO) inpatient hospitalizations and emergency department (ED) visits among California residents. Inpatient hospitalization data are aggregated into 5-year groupings for years 2000-2007. ED visit data are annual for years 2005-2007. Types of CO poisonings are broken out by fire-related, non-fire-related, and unknown cause. The data are stratified by county, year, and fire-relatedness.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:abstract>          <gmd:purpose>             <gco:CharacterString>To provide data that is consistent with the National Environmental Public Health Tracking Network guidance for creating the CO poisoning inpatient hospitalization and emegency department visit Nationally Consistent Data and Measures (NCDMs).</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:purpose>          <gmd:status>             <gmd:MD_ProgressCode CO poisoning hospitalizations are selected based on admitting diagnosis coding. The California EPHT Program receives calendar year hospitalization and emergency department data annually from the Office of Statewide Health Planning and Development (OSHPD). Further information on OSHPD is located at: www.oshpd.ca.gov. All state licensed hospitals in California are required by California Health and Safety Code to report to OSHPD data elements for each inpatient discharged from the hospital and each emergency department visit. The facilities submit their data via the Medical Information Reporting for California (MIRCal), an on-line data transmission method. Additional fields are computed by OSHPD.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:supplementalInformation>       </gmd:MD_DataIdentification>    </gmd:identificationInfo>    <gmd:contentInfo><!-- translated from eainfo to MD_FeatureCatalogueDescription--><gmd:MD_FeatureCatalogueDescription>          <gmd:includedWithDataset>             <gco:Boolean>false</gco:Boolean>          </gmd:includedWithDataset>          <gmd:featureCatalogueCitation gco:nilReason="unknown">             <gmd:CI_Citation>                <gmd:title>                   <gco:CharacterString>Entity and Attribute Information</gco:CharacterString>                </gmd:title>                <gmd:date gco:nilReason="unknown"/>                <gmd:otherCitationDetails>                   <gco:CharacterString>Entity and Attribute Overview: This data contains the following fields: Cnty_FIPS Start_Date End_Date Measure_ID Measure_VA. For hospitalizations, case counts are aggregated into 5-year intervals according to admission year, county, and type of CO-poisoning. For ED visits, case counts are annual by year, county, and type of CO-poisoning. The types of intentional CO-poisonings included are: fire-related, non-fire related, and unknown cause. Each year, OSHPD compiles the data from all hospitals to create the Patient Discharge Database (PDD) and Emergency Department database. Each year, CEHTP obtains the PDD and ED dataset from OSHPD and creates datasets to be used for public health surveillance, while maintaining confidentiality. This dataset on the CEHTP portal includes hospitalizations unintentional carbon monoxide poisonings for the years 2000 to 2007. Each event is identified by looking at all diagnosis codes (up to 24) based on the International Classification of Disease, Ninth Revision, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM). Each hospitalization event is identified based on date of admission into the hospital, rather than date of discharge. Counts, rates, and confidence intervals were calculated by county, age-group, gender, and race/ethnicity. To calculate rates, we use population data from the California Department of Finance (DOF). DOF uses year 2000 population data collected by the U.S. Census Bureau and takes into account survival rates, migration patterns, and fertility rates for California to project the California population by county, race/ethnicity, age, and gender for 2000-2050 (State of California, Department of Finance, Population Projections for California and Its Counties 2000-2050, Sacramento, California, July 2007).
